  "response": "Looking at the scan, the `weak_test_signal` findings split into two groups: tests with zero assertions (`crime_00016` through `crime_00027`) and tests with only weak matchers (`crime_00065` through `crime_00078`). For an **esbuild plugin regression** specifically, one finding jumps out:\n\n**`crime_00024` — `test/index.test.ts` lines 537–548**\n\n> - \"test: \\\"native-node-module plugin should handle *.node(.js) import properly\\\"\"\n> - \"0 expect/assert calls\"\n> - \"lines 537-548\"\n\nI'd strengthen this one first. The reasoning:\n\n1. **It's the only weak-test finding that names an esbuild plugin in its title.** Every other zero-assertion test is about `--dts`, `experimentalDts`, `graphql`, `removeNodeProtocol`, `tsconfig`, or `vue` — none of those would explain an *esbuild plugin* regression slipping through. This one literally says `\"native-node-module plugin should handle *.node(.js) import properly\"`.\n2. **It has zero assertions, not just weak ones** (confidence `0.88`). The test name makes a behavioural promise — \"should handle … properly\" — and then the body proves nothing. CI will stay green as long as the bundle doesn't throw, even if the plugin silently stops handling `*.node`/`*.node.js` imports correctly. That is precisely the failure mode the user described.\n\n**The assertion I'd add:** read the bundled output and assert that `*.node` imports survive as runtime `require()` calls instead of being inlined or stripped. Concretely, something like:\n\n```ts\nconst contents = await getFileContents(outputFiles, 'index.js')\nexpect(contents).toMatch(/require\\(['\"].+\\.node['\"]\\)/)\nexpect(contents).not.toContain('Cannot find module')\n```\n\nThe exact regex depends on what the native-node-module plugin is supposed to emit, but the principle is: the test's name promises the plugin handles `*.node(.js)` imports — so the assertion must inspect the output and confirm the import was handled in the expected shape. Without that, the test only proves the build didn't crash, which is exactly the gap the regression exploited.",
